%% - \Abstract{} almost as usual
\Abstract{
We describe the \proglang{R} package \pkg{uGMAR}, which provides tools for estimating and analyzing the Gaussian mixture autoregressive model, the Student's $t$ mixture autoregressive model, and the Gaussian and Student's $t$ mixture autoregressive model. These three models constitute an appealing family of mixture autoregressive models that we call the GSMAR models. The model parameters are estimated with the method of maximum likelihood by running multiple rounds of a two-phase estimation procedure in which a genetic algorithm is used to find starting values for a gradient based method. For evaluating the adequacy of the estimated models, \pkg{uGMAR} utilizes so-called quantile residuals and provides functions for graphical diagnostics as well as for calculating formal diagnostic tests. \pkg{uGMAR} also enables to simulate from the GSMAR processes and to forecast future values of the process using a simulation-based Monte Carlo method. We illustrate the use of \pkg{uGMAR} with the monthly U.S. interest rate spread between the 10-year and 1-year Treasury rates. This vignette was created with the Journal of Statistical Software style.
}

